<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chemicals Could Create No-Mow Lawn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                          *MICHAEL PEARSON   	
</P>
<P>
	CARBONDALE, Ill. (AP) -- Dale Palscher doesn't just dislike  
mowing his lawn -- he hates it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll have the kids do it, the neighbors, my wife, I don't  
care,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not quite time for him to sell off his mower, but an  
emerging group of chemicals could someday take most of the mowing 
out of his yard work. 
</P>
<P>
	For years, golf course superintendents and sports field managers  
have used plant growth regulators to keep their greens trim. 
</P>
<P>
	The idea hasn't yet caught on with homeowners, in part because  
the products are hard to apply and have had a reputation for doing 
more damage than good if improperly used. 
</P>
<P>
	But newer, more foolproof versions of the products are entering  
the professional market, leading some to believe homeowners also 
could eventually buy something that would give them a thick, green, 
no-mow lawn. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not a sure market like fertilizer,'' said Ken Diesburg,  
who studies turf grasses at Southern Illinois University in 
Carbondale. ``But at least one of the lawn-care companies is 
thinking about using it, which is a first.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Diesburg has been studying the active ingredient in a newly  
released professional product from Rhone Poulenc Ag Co., called 
Proxy. 
</P>
<P>
	He has found that the newest generation of growth regulators has  
more tolerance for mistakes and does less damage if improperly 
used. 
</P>
<P>
	Growth regulators, which began appearing in the 1980s, slow or  
stop grass growth by shifting the plants' hormonal balance, 
Diesburg said. 
</P>
<P>
	Proxy works by shifting the plant's growing energy from up to  
out. Instead of taller shoots, grass plants produce branches, 
making a thick turf that might need mowing just twice a summer, 
Diesburg said. 
</P>
<P>
	It works best on Kentucky bluegrass, the most popular grass for  
golf course fairways in much of the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	However, current products require precise application. Although  
Proxy is more forgiving when people overlap areas when spraying it, 
it is still not easy to apply, Diesburg said. 
</P>
<P>
	And the Scotts Co., an Ohio-based manufacturer of lawn-care  
products, found additional factors standing in the way when it 
tried unsuccessfully to market its PGR growth regulator to 
consumers several years ago, said Scotts grass expert Ashton 
Ritchie. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of them enjoy taking care of the lawn, how it smells  
after they mow it, how it looks after they mow it. And people who 
don't mow don't tend to buy lawn care products, either,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, a growth regulator would be appealing to homeowners if  
manufacturers can overcome the technical hurdles, said Alan Marcus, 
director of the Iowa State University Center for Historical Studies 
of Technology and Science. 
</P>
<P>
	``People for whatever reason think they have too much to do and  
too little time to do it,'' he said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
