<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thompson Takes 3 Swimming Golds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Jenny Thompson had enough energy left for a  
third gold medal, if not a second world record. 
</P>
<P>
	That was good enough for Thompson to be chosen best female  
swimmer at the World Short-Course Championships Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The weary Thompson capped a grueling meet by winning the  
100-meter butterfly in 57.65 seconds. Her December 1998 time of 
56.90 is one of three world records she holds. 
</P>
<P>
	During the meet, Thompson also broke one world record -- in an  
event where she didn't win the gold medal, because she dropped out 
after the heats. 
</P>
<P>
	That same day, she won the 50-meter butterfly and 100 freestyle.  
After taking second in the 50 freestyle Saturday, she rebounded 
with her victory in the 100 butterfly. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am extremely tired from all the racing I've been doing, and  
it cost me,'' Thompson said. ``I was hoping to go a little faster 
and break the world record, but it wasn't there tonight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Looking ahead to the 2000 Olympics, Thompson said, ``One step at  
a time -- first the Pan Pacific this summer, then Sydney.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly after Thompson's victory, two Japanese women did their  
best to overshadow her. 
</P>
<P>
	Mai Nakamura and Masami Tanaka sent their relay team off to a  
big early lead, and Japan broke the world record in the 400 medley 
relay. Tanaka already had swept all three individual breaststroke 
races, breaking one world record, and Nakamura took two of the 
three individual backstroke events. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meet's final race, Australia made amends for a  
disqualification in the men's 800 freestyle relay and broke the 
world record in the medley relay. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, world records fell in seven events. Each was worth  
$15,000 thanks to rewards offered for the first time by FINA, 
swimming's governing body. 
</P>
<P>
	Nakamura and Tanaka gave Japan a 2.7-second lead in the relay  
after 200 meters, and Ayari Aoyama and Sumika Minamoto finished off 
the victory in 3:57.62, beating the mark of 3:57.73 set by China in 
1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Australia's men swam the medley relay in 3:29.88, breaking their  
2-year-old mark of 3:30.66. 
</P>
<P>
	The record came two days after the Australians were disqualified  
in the freestyle relay for not following their entry list order in 
the heats. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan finished with six golds after picking up three Sunday --  
the relay, Tanaka's victory in the 100 breaststroke and Nakamura's 
in the 200 backstroke, where she missed a world record by .4 
second. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson accounted for all three of the U.S. gold medals.  
</P>
<P>
	World long-course champion Kurt Grote led midway through the 200  
breaststroke, but faded and finished fifth at 2:09.47, compared to 
the winning time of 2:08.72 by Australia's Phil Rodgers. 
</P>
<P>
	Australian Matthew Dunn was chosen best male swimmer of the  
meet. He won two of the three individual medleys after winning a 
duel in the 200 with Britain's James Hickman. 
</P>
<P>
	Australian Grant Hackett won the men's 1,500 freestyle at  
14:32.87, more than 12 seconds slower than his world record. 
</P>
<P>
	Slovakia's Martina Moravcova earned her second and third golds,  
winning the women's 200 individual medley and 200 freestyle within 
90 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Others who became double gold medalists Sunday were Sweden's  
Lars Frolander, winner of the men's 100 freestyle; Britain's Mark 
Foster, who won the 50 butterfly, and Cuba's Rodolfo Falcon, winner 
of the 100 backstroke. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
