<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Helling Hopes for Encore in '99 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Rick Helling went into last season as  
the sixth starter in the Texas Rangers' five-man rotation. He goes 
into this season as the team's ace. 
</P>
<P>
	Helling pitched so well last spring that manager Johnny Oates  
had to give him a shot in the regular season. He ended up winning 
his first six starts and going 20-7, entrenching him as Texas' No. 
1 starter. 
</P>
<P>
	The burning question for the Rangers this season is whether  
Helling -- who had never won more than five games in a season and 
had just 11 career wins before last year -- can repeat his 1998 
success. The answer could determine whether the team will 
successfully defend its AL West title. 
</P>
<P>
	Helling's first test comes Monday as Texas' opening day starter  
against Detroit. Brian Moehler (14-13), who also had a breakout 
year in 1998, starts for the Tigers. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I was in Florida, I remember Al Leiter telling me that  
every year is a proving year,'' Helling said. ``If you're coming 
off a good year, you have to prove that you can do it again. If 
you're coming off a bad year, you have to prove it was a fluke.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Helling and the Rangers may learn their fates very soon. After  
opening with three games against the Tigers, Texas is host to 
Anaheim, its top division rival, for four games. A week later, the 
Rangers start a 15-game stretch that includes 11 games against the 
New York Yankees, Cleveland and Boston -- the other three AL playoff 
teams last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Helling's first six starts are likely to include Detroit,  
Anaheim, Cleveland and either Oakland or Seattle -- plus the Yankees 
twice. 
</P>
<P>
	A bigger issue for Texas is the health of Rafael Palmeiro, John  
Wetteland and Mark McLemore. Although all three are expected to be 
available Monday, Palmeiro and Wetteland missed most of the spring 
recovering from injuries, and McLemore tweaked his oft-injured legs 
over the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Palmeiro, who had operations on his right knee in February and  
March, got in a lot of work the last week of camp and looked sharp 
in recent days. He's likely to spend the first few games at 
designated hitter, keeping his $45 million bat in the lineup and 
preserving his status as the most durable player this decade after 
Cal Ripken Jr. 
</P>
<P>
	Wetteland's surgically repaired right arm was doing fine when he  
severely strained his right ankle. He took off more time than he 
wanted to, but it seems to have worked as he's been dominant in his 
last few appearances. 
</P>
<P>
	McLemore had been saying he feels his best since 1996, the last  
season he didn't go on the disabled list. But that was until 
slightly straining his left hamstring Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Most people were surprised to see Helling among the league  
leaders in wins last season. Helling wasn't. He always believed he 
could succeed if given the chance. 
</P>
<P>
	Helling broke in with the Rangers in 1994 and started nine  
games. He split time in the majors and minors the next year, then 
was traded to Florida in 1996. The Marlins used him mainly in 
relief, then traded him back to Texas in 1997. The Rangers weren't 
set on using him as a starter until he proved he deserved the job 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Helling's strength is a good understanding of how to pitch. He  
has good movement on his fastball and likes to throw it high in the 
strike zone. He relies more on fly balls than strikeouts (164 in 
216 1-3 innings last year) and he's averaged about one walk every 
three innings over his career. 
</P>
<P>
	By going 5-0 in his last seven starts last year, Helling proved  
he could rise to the occasion. His 4.41 ERA -- the fifth-highest 
ever for a 20-game winner -- showed he knew how to take advantage of 
the whopping 6.61 runs per game Texas scored for him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think that I've done the best that I can -- that's what  
motivates me,'' Helling said. ``In no way did last year make me 
lazy. I've worked just as hard as if I'd been 7-20.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
