<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Welcomes Castilla </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *AP Photos    	
</P>
<P>
	MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) -- He was more than 1,000 miles away from  
his hometown and his Colorado Rockies were billed as the visitor. 
But the thousands of fans made it clear Sunday: Vinny Castilla was 
at home. 
</P>
<P>
	They screamed with each two-fingered wave he directed into the  
stands. They gave him a standing ovation when his name was 
announced in the lineup. The song ``Matador'' played over the 
loudspeakers before every at-bat. 
</P>
<P>
	And they crushed into the railing, desperately thrusting  
baseballs in his direction and yelling ``Vinny! Sign mine!'' when 
he signed a few autographs before the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were all over there pushing and shoving,'' Castilla said  
after retreating to the dugout. ``Something bad's going to 
happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Castilla came through on the fans expectations going 4-for-5 and  
scoring one run in the Rockies 8-2 victory against the San Diego 
Padres. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only thing missing is a home run,'' said Luis Farias, a  
30-year-old fan. 
</P>
<P>
	The fans in the northern Mexican city of Monterrey, only two  
hours from the Texas border, adore Castilla, who hails from the 
southern state of Oaxaca, but had never played in Monterrey Stadium 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	Oaxaca is the poorest state in Mexico, where the minimum wage is  
$3 a day -- far less than Castilla's $24 million, four-year 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the San Diego Padres were considered the home team,  
almost all of the caps, jerseys and banners in the stands read 
Colorado Rockies. 
</P>
<P>
	Five brothers colored their hair purple and wore white shirts  
with purple lettering that spelled out ``Vinny's'' on the front and 
``Rules'' on the back. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like when (Fernando) Valenzuela played with the Dodgers,  
we all rooted for the Dodgers,'' said Ruben Rodriguez, a 
37-year-old computer programmer. ``Now with Vinny we're with the 
Rockies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rodriguez, who said he was a soccer fan, was taking his  
9-year-old son Ruben Eduardo to his first baseball game. 
</P>
<P>
	Castilla himself didn't say much before the game but couldn't  
wipe a broad grin off his face as he warmed up. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel at home,'' he said in the dugout, slipping a wad of  
Skoal into his cheek. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference, Castilla said he hoped to be a pioneer for  
baseball in Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope what I'm doing helps a lot of people, like what  
Fernando Valenzuela did helped me,'' he said. ``People are 
expecting a home run from Vinny Castilla, and I'll do my best.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Once Castilla emerged for batting practice, Rockies' public  
relations director Jay Alves ran interference, pushing away the 
cameramen and reporters who strayed too close. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Castilla, despite his phenomenal batting statistics,  
isn't as big of a star in Colorado as some other players. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's huge here. There, it's not even close,'' he said. ``He  
might be the most underrated player in baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Teammate Dante Bichette, no stranger to fame himself, said  
Castilla seemed to be holding up well. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's not too much the nervous type,'' he said. ``It's a lot of  
fun. I couldn't wait to get here and see the reception he's 
getting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Jim Leyland said he welcomed the attention Castilla was  
getting but hoped it wouldn't detract from the game itself. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want Vinny to have his day and all, but we also have to  
realize this is a real game,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
