<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Welcomes Castilla </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *AP Photos    	
</P>
<P>
	MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) -- He was more than 1,000 miles away from  
his hometown and his Colorado Rockies were billed as the visitor. 
But the thousands of fans made it clear Sunday: Vinny Castilla was 
at home. 
</P>
<P>
	They screamed with each two-fingered wave he directed into the  
stands. They gave him a standing ovation when his name was 
announced in the lineup. The song ``Matador'' played over the 
loudspeakers before every at-bat. 
</P>
<P>
	And they crushed into the railing, desperately thrusting  
baseballs in his direction and yelling ``Vinny! Sign mine!'' when 
he signed a few autographs before the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a good night for me,'' Castilla said after the Rockies  
8-2 victory against the San Diego Padres. ``I tried my last two 
at-bats to hit a home run. It didn't happen, but I'm happy for the 
win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Castilla came through on the fans expectations going 4-for-5 and  
scoring one run. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only thing missing is a home run,'' said Luis Farias, a  
30-year-old fan. 
