<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Singer Deborah Cox Talks to Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Deborah Cox says she's enjoying life on the top of  
the U.S. charts as Canada's first R&AMP;B star -- but don't call her a 
diva. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not,'' she told The Boston Globe in Sunday's editions.  
``I'm really a settled, down-to earth person. I treat people the 
way I like to be treated and that's just with respect. I've always 
been very down-to-earth and not fazed by the music business, or by 
what other people do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cox, of Toronto, made history this year with the longest-running  
No. 1 R&AMP;B hit of all time -- 14 weeks topping the charts with 
``Nobody's Supposed to Be Here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She'll be heading out on tour with R. Kelly this spring and Cox  
says she's hoping to exceed her accomplishments on her current and 
second album ``One Wish.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's all about longevity,'' said Cox, 25. ``I want to be an  
artist, who 10 years from now, won't be a has-been. And past of 
that longevity is singing really great songs... Every album we put 
together, it's about the song.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
