<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> INS Raids Worry Asparagus Farmers / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KENNEWICK, Wash. (AP) -- With harvest close at hand, asparagus  
growers are worried that a threatened federal search for illegal 
workers will leave them shorthanded. 
</P>
<P>
	They fear the Immigration and Naturalization Service will raid  
farms as part of a crackdown that included Yakima fruit warehouses 
in February. That could leave asparagus growers strapped for labor 
for a second straight year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't like having this threat hanging over our heads,''  
said Mike Gempler, director of the Washington Growers League. 
``There is the possibility of losing a sizable portion of acres 
during critical work on a perishable crop.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the Yakima raids, which resulted in the firings of about  
600 employees, INS officials promised more enforcement throughout 
eastern Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal agency is on a nationwide push to reduce the number  
of illegal aliens by focusing on industries that traditionally have 
had high numbers of undocumented workers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been told (INS agents) are coming down this way,'' said  
Bryan Alford, a grower in Franklin County. 
</P>
<P>
	Farm workers are grating under the pressure, too. The Yakima  
firings were condemned by numerous worker advocate groups and the 
local Roman Catholic bishop. 
</P>
<P>
	For asparagus, timing is everything. Spears that aren't cut when  
ready often grow beyond marketable size by the next day, said Mike 
Harker of the Washington Asparagus Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Roughly 6,500 workers cut the state's asparagus crop, harvesting  
22,000 acres in about six weeks of backbreaking work. 
</P>
<P>
	Harker said there are ``significant numbers of illegal workers  
in the labor force'' -- a condition farmers say they don't want but 
can't do much about. 
</P>
<P>
	Kent McMullen, a cherry and Asian pear farmer near Ringold, said  
job seekers can show him any of 28 different pieces of 
identification. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have seen ID that I suspected was maybe counterfeit, but I  
am not an expert, and I am not the police force, nor should any 
farmer be,'' McMullen said. 
</P>
<P>
	An INS strike during peak harvest could force a farm out of  
business, said McMullen, who wants legal workers to be issued an 
electronic card that can be scanned by computer and verified like a 
personal check. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington and California each produce about 40 percent of the  
nation's asparagus. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington's 1998 crop was worth $40 million, Harker said.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- While searching for the pesky pink  
hibiscus mealybug, University of Florida researchers instead found 
the papaya mealybug, which eats the sap of hibiscus, papaya, 
cassava and other plants. 
</P>
<P>
	As the insects feed on sap, they attack plants by injecting a  
toxic substance into leaves, stunting the plants' growth and 
causing them to become gnarled. 
</P>
<P>
	``This discovery of a pest we didn't even suspect was here shows  
how easily alien insect species can cross our leaky borders and 
wreak havoc on our yards, farms and plant nurseries,'' said 
Marjorie Hoy, a scholar in biological control at the university's 
Institute of Food and Agricultural Sciences. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-six samples of the insect have been found in the state.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're concerned because this pest has been found on both  
coasts and could have spread to other locations,'' said Avas Hamon, 
an entomologist in the Division of Plant Industry of the Florida 
Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services. 
</P>
<P>
	The Florida discoveries are the only ones in the continental  
United States, said Dale Meyerdirk, who heads the U.S. Department 
of Agriculture's mealybug control program in Riverdale, Md. 
</P>
<P>
	USDA officials are searching in Mexico and Central America for  
natural enemies of the papaya mealybug. Those enemies are to be 
tested on the department's papaya mealybug colony in the U.S. 
Virgin Islands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
