<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Review of 'Tongue of a Bird' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- For all its talk about flight, ``Tongue of a  
Bird,'' Ellen McLaughlin's murky memory play, curiously refuses to 
fly. 
</P>
<P>
	This earthbound meditation, which opened Sunday at  
off-Broadway's Public Theater, is the story of a female 
search-and-rescue pilot looking for a little girl abducted in the 
Adirondacks. 
</P>
<P>
	``The particular lost thing -- I've always found it,'' says  
Maxine, the pilot scouring the snowy wilderness for the missing 
child. What Maxine can't quite locate is her own life, specifically 
memories of her mother. The older woman committed suicide and now 
comes back -- dressed in a leather flying coat, goggles and helmet -- 
to haunt her daughter. She hovers about five feet above Maxine's 
bed, swooping and somersaulting her way into her daughter's psyche. 
</P>
<P>
	Mom isn't the only person Maxine encounters in her journey to  
self-awareness. She must contend with the missing girl's 
contentious mother; her own grandmother, a Polish immigrant whose 
health is failing, and the missing youngster herself, bloodied but 
very much a presence in this play. 
</P>
<P>
	The characters carry on odd, lyrical conversations that slowly  
push the plot forward, without shedding much light on themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	What occasionally lifts ``Tongue of a Bird'' out of the obtuse  
is its cast, starting with a radiant Cherry Jones as the indecisive 
pilot. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, a Tony winner for her performance in ``The Heiress,'' is  
an actress of enormous conviction. She grounds Maxine in a reality 
that the play never quite achieves. Jones' manner is charming, 
simple and straightforward. 
</P>
<P>
	Maxine's conversations with her dotty grandmother are funny and  
fresh, particularly because Elizabeth Wilson gives the older woman 
a gentle, almost whimsical quality. 
</P>
<P>
	Melissa Leo emphasizes the harshness of the distraught mother of  
the missing girl. As the object of Maxine's search, young Julia 
McIlvaine is fine, brash and a bit boisterous. Sharon Lawrence is 
left with the evening's least rewarding -- and most difficult -- 
role, the ethereal mother. In her aviator outfit, the airborne 
Lawrence looks like a cross between Amelia Earhart and Peter Pan. 
</P>
<P>
	Director Lisa Peterson can't quite get a handle on the play's  
fanciful swoops and swirls. Neither can the production staff, which 
had problems with lighting and sound cues at a recent preview 
performance. 
</P>
<P>
	But then ``Tongue of a Bird'' never soars, finding itself lost  
in cloudy pretensions that don't allow this wordy play to really 
take off. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990404.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 12:13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rays Open 2nd Season in Baltimore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- By theory, opening day is merely one game in  
162, the first step in a marathon that stretches through the entire 
summer and finally concludes in early October. 
</P>
<P>
	For the Baltimore Orioles, however, the season opener can often  
be a harbinger of things to come. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the past five years, Baltimore has gone 3-2 on opening day.  
Each time they won -- in 1994, '96 and '97 -- the Orioles finished 
over .500. They were 63-49 before the 1994 strike and reached the 
playoffs in both 1996 and '97. 
</P>
<P>
	When they lost their season opener, the Orioles ended up with a  
losing record. That includes last year, when a 4-1 loss to Kansas 
City proved to be the starting point of a disappointing season that 
ended with a 79-83 record -- and that with the highest payroll in 
baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles, naturally, hope to get off with a win Monday when  
they send Mike Mussina to the mound in the opener against the Tampa 
Bay Devil Rays. But no one on the team is expecting a horrid season 
if Baltimore fails to win. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just one game. That's the way you have to look at it,''  
Mussina said Sunday on the eve of his fifth opening-day start. 
``It's great to win the first game, great to get off on a good 
note. But if you don't, it's by no means the end of the season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Will Clark, who is preparing for his first opening day with the  
Orioles, was told of the connection between opening day success and 
regular-season prosperity. He quickly waved his hand, dismissing it 
as mere coincidence. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know what that is to me? A meaningless statistic,'' he  
said. ``Sure you want to win on opening day. There's a lot more 
adrenaline and emotion than in spring training, but it's just 
another game in the standings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles' opening day lineup includes four players who  
weren't with the team last year: Clark, Albert Belle, Charles 
Johnson and Jeff Conine, who will serve as the designated hitter. 
</P>
<P>
	The Devil Rays also have a new look as they enter their second  
season. The most notable addition is Jose Canseco, who brings his 
hit-or-miss bat south from Toronto to help an offense that finished 
last in the majors in homers and runs scored in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite finishing in the top five in the AL in ERA and fielding  
percentage, Tampa Bay went 63-99 in its first season and finished 
one notch behind Baltimore in the AL East cellar. But the Devil 
Rays won seven of 12 from the Orioles, including a four-game road 
sweep in May that left Baltimore with a 20-23 record and in a 
comeback mode for the rest of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``They came in here and surprised us,'' Baltimore reliever Jesse  
Orosco said. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest disappointment for the Devil Rays last year was the  
play of veterans Fred McGriff, Paul Sorrento, Wilson Alvarez and 
Roberto Hernandez. All came to camp this year determined to be more 
productive. 
</P>
<P>
	``You could walk in here the first day and tell there was a  
difference,'' manager Larry Rothschild said. ``I won't say they 
were embarrassed, but I think a lot of guys were not pleased with 
how they did last year and they've come in and worked very hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rothschild has chosen Alvarez to start Monday ahead of Rolando  
Arrojo, who has been slowed by stiff back. Alvarez pitched a 
no-hitter against the Orioles in 1991 but stumbled to a 6-14 record 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're giving me another chance. I know they wanted Arrojo to  
pitch and he deserves it,'' Alvarez said. ``The way he pitched last 
year, he deserves to be No. 1 here. It's too bad he's hurt.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
