<HEADLINE> Mariners Play Last Kingdome Opener </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- The Chicago White Sox had the worst pitchers in  
the American League last season and the Seattle Mariners' staff 
wasn't much better. 
</P>
<P>
	No surprise, both teams open a new season Monday night with a  
lot of the same old questions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every time we get the opportunity to get an out, we have to  
get it, because we don't have the offense or pitching to get us out 
of it,'' second-year White Sox manager Jerry Manuel said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the final Mariners' opener in the Kingdome, Mariners manager  
Lou Piniella will use left-hander Jeff Fassero against James 
Baldwin. 
</P>
<P>
	Fassero, 36, is coming off surgery this winter to remove bone  
chips from his pitching elbow. He had a 13.19 ERA this spring, 
giving up 21 earned runs in six innings in his last two exhibition 
starts. 
</P>
<P>
	Baldwin was 13-6 in 24 starts for the White Sox last season.  
</P>
<P>
	``When you go with experienced pitchers, you have a pretty good  
idea of what to expect,'' Piniella said. ``When you go with a lot 
of young pitchers, you're operating in unchartered waters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Mariners still have a powerful offense, with All-Stars Ken  
Griffey Jr. and Alex Rodriguez, but their pitching is suspect, too. 
</P>
<P>
	With Randy Johnson now pitching for the Arizona Diamondbacks,  
Seattle is hoping young pitchers like Freddy Garcia can come 
through. Garcia, 22, came to the Mariners from Houston in a trade 
for Johnson last July 31. 
</P>
<P>
	In spring training, Garcia, a right-hander, established himself  
as the Mariners' No. 3 starter. 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, the Mariners were favored to win the AL West, but  
were a disappointing nine games under .500 to wind up third behind 
Texas and Anaheim. 
</P>
<P>
	Seattle's pitching staff tied for 10th in the league with  
Detroit with a 4.93 ERA last season. The White Sox had a team ERA 
of 5.22, worst in the AL. 
</P>
<P>
	After Baldwin, Chicago's starters will be Mike Sirotka, Jim  
Parque and John Snyder. 
</P>
<P>
	Gone from the White Sox are Albert Belle and Robin Ventura,  
leaving Frank Thomas left to supply most of the offense in a lineup 
that includes newcomer Paul Konerko. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's not even an issue at all,'' Thomas said of Chicago's  
losses of Belle and Ventura. 
</P>
<P>
	Belle and Ventura combined for 69 homers and 243 RBIs last  
season. The White Sox let Belle and Ventura go as free agents -- 
Belle to Baltimore and Ventura to the New York Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	Mariners fans lost a longtime target Saturday night when the  
team traded reliever Bobby Ayala to Montreal for 6-foot-10 
minor-league pitching prospect Jimmy Turman. 
</P>
<P>
	Ayala was 1-10 with a 7.29 ERA in 62 relief appearances with  
Seattle last season. 
</P>
<P>
	In their 23rd season, the Mariners will move into their new  
home, $498 million Safeco Field, on July 15. 
</P>
<P>
	Hank Aaron, who holds the major league record with 755 career  
home runs, will throw out the ceremonial first pitch Monday night. 
Then he'll watch Griffey, a player who could break his record, play 
center field for the Mariners. 
</P>
<P>
	In 10 seasons, Griffey has 350 homers, including 56 last season  
when he led the league for the second time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
