<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Attacks Gore on Internet Claim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With Vice President Al Gore heading to Silicon  
Valley this week to raise campaign funds, a Republican group 
intends to ridicule him in a television commercial for claiming to 
have taken the initiative in creating the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	``Reality check. The Internet was created in 1969 by the  
Pentagon,'' says the advertisement, which was financed by the 
Republican Leadership Council. 
</P>
<P>
	It also taunts the vice president for saying he had lived on a  
farm and his father taught him how to do chores in the hot sun. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not quite. Gore grew up in a top floor suite of a luxury hotel  
in Washington, D.C.,'' the ad continues, although it omits the fact 
that Gore's family also owned a farm in Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	The commercial also notes Gore's claim for having worked on  
reinventing government, a major project during the Clinton 
administration. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yeah right,'' the ad states. ``Earth to Gore. Stop trying to  
reinvent reality.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's campaign manager, Craig Smith, shot back: ``No half-baked  
attack ad by the Republicans will hide the fact that they are 
offering no vision for America's future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said Gore's leadership in Internet technology is genuine  
and he saved taxpayers ``millions'' with his campaign to make 
government more efficient. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Miller, a spokesman for the group that paid for the ad,  
said it will run over 50 times in two days in the area around 
Silicon Valley, including on broadcast stations in San Francisco, 
at a cost of roughly $30,000. Additionally, the group bought a 
smaller amount of time on CNN programs and in the Washington, D.C., 
area. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was about four years ago now that Dick Morris and Bill  
Clinton sat down in the White House and designed some issue ads 
talking about Bob Dole,'' Miller said of the commercials that 
helped Clinton on his way to re-election. ``I'd rather learn from 
history than repeat it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	At 2,826 eye-glazing pages, the quarterly ``Statement of  
Disbursements of the House'' details how the House of 
Representatives spent its money in the last three months of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	It lists everything from staff salaries to the cost of newspaper  
subscriptions for lawmakers' offices, from coffee and bottled water 
for congressional offices, to reimbursements for taxi rides for 
lawmakers and staff. 
</P>
<P>
	One of those pages records federal funds returned to the  
government by House members ``for reduction of public debt.'' In 
all, 14 of 435 House members made the list, and returned 
$13,460.83, according to the report. 
</P>
<P>
	The largest gift listed was $3,700, from Democratic Rep. Lane  
Evans, D-Ill., while the smallest was from Republican Rep. Richard 
Baker of Louisiana, at $99.61. 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	Top leaders of the House and Senate are traveling widely during  
the current two-week congressional recess. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., was in Europe last week,  
leading a delegation of lawmakers. The Democratic leader, Rep. 
Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., led a group to India. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate's top Democrat, Tom Daschle of South Dakota, was  
heading on six-day trip to South America, with stops in Brazil, 
Chile and Argentina. 
</P>
<P>
	Also expected to accompany Daschle were the Senate's  
second-ranking Democrat, Sen. Harry Reid of Nevada, as well as 
Democrat Byron Dorgan of North Dakota and Sen. Ben Nighthorse 
Campbell, a Colorado Republican. The group planned to discuss trade 
and economic security issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Alone among the top leaders of Congress, Senate Majority Leader  
Trent Lott was not going abroad during the break. An aide said Lott 
was spending most of his time in Mississippi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
