<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Paintball Has Risk of Eye Injury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A full-face paintball shield, with its  
big-eyed goggles, can make a player look like Darth Vader. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors think that's a cool look, especially when the  
alternative is not to be able to look at all. Potentially blinding 
eye injuries can happen to a player who succumbs to the impulse to 
remove the shield. 
</P>
<P>
	In his study of paintball injury cases, seven of 11 people who  
had taken off the eye protection wound up legally blind in one eye, 
said Lt. Col. Allen B. Thach, an ophthalmologist at Walter Reed 
Army Medical Center. 
</P>
<P>
	The combat simulation game is supposed to be played while  
wearing face protection that includes clear, impact-resistant 
plastic over the eyes. Doctors and paintball experts agree that 
most players -- as well as virtually all paintball game centers -- 
insist on eye protection. 
</P>
<P>
	But it may be tempting to remove the shield after a paintball  
lands on a lens or if the goggles fog up, Thach said. 
</P>
<P>
	``During the heat of the battle, as you may say, you may not be  
thinking straight, and take off the goggles without thinking,'' 
Thach said. 
</P>
<P>
	Doing so exposes the eye to the impact of a missile of  
gelatine-enclosed paint fired from a carbon dioxide-powered gun at 
300-400 feet per second, according to Thach's article in the 
medical journal Ophthalmology. 
</P>
<P>
	It is not the only cause of injury; two other people in the  
study were hit by ricochets in which the projectile traveled up 
under the face mask. But the experts consider this unusual and say 
the risk can be reduced with the newer masks. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't find the paint itself causing the problem,'' said Dr.  
Nick Mamalis, professor of ophthalmology at the University of Utah, 
who also has seen paintball injuries. ``It's the ball the paint is 
in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The patients he has seen often were able to blink in time to  
keep paint out of their eyes, but the gelatine of the ball damaged 
the eye by the force of the impact, Mamalis said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Thach's article, patients suffered such major injuries as  
hemorrhages, retinal detachments and ruptures of the eyeball. 
Mamalis also reported cases of glaucoma, elevated pressure in the 
eye, caused by the impact of the ball or by damage to structures 
that allow drainage of liquid from the eye. 
</P>
<P>
	The risk is probably very low when eye protection is used  
properly, the doctors said. Exactly how low cannot be determined, 
in part because there is no industry association to keep track of 
the number of injuries, or even estimate the total number of 
players. 
</P>
<P>
	The protective equipment itself is sturdy, according to Bob  
Lowry, sales marketing manager for Scott USA, a manufacturer in Sun 
Valley, Idaho. The goggles have thicker polycarbonate plastic than 
is used in motorcycle faceguards, he said. Some paintball 
faceguards have tearaway plastic sheeting on the front, so a player 
can clear the visual field simply by ripping off the 
paint-spattered top sheet, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the industry self-polices. At reputable paintball centers,  
employees order players to wear eye protection, signs notify 
players to do it, and judges take players out of the game if they 
lose their protection, Thach said. 
</P>
<P>
	The bigger risk area may be in unsupervised play -- ``renegade  
paintball, Joe and his cousin going out in the back yard,'' said 
Bill Mills of Lake Park, Fla., a longtime player who oversees 
Warpig, an Internet site devoted to the game. However, because 
there are no data on unsupervised games, he can't be sure, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	And the attitudes of the players, typically teen-age boys and  
young men, may play a part, Mamalis said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Young males tend not to pay attention to things such as ocular  
protection, even if it's required,'' Mamalis said. ``I asked one 
man, `Why did you not wear them,' and he said, `Well, they didn't 
make me,' and he was quite ticked off that I even asked him.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
