<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Contrite Irabu Returns to Yankees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Hideki Irabu returned to the New York Yankees  
today and apologized for his absence. Then, he took part in a drill 
covering first base -- a one-man drill. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Irabu's failure to cover the bag last week that prompted  
owner George Steinbrenner to call the Japanese pitcher a ``fat ... 
toad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Irabu stayed behind at the team's spring camp at Tampa, Fla.,  
while the Yankees traveled Thursday to the West Coast for a pair of 
exhibition games. But with the support of Steinbrenner, Irabu 
rejoined the club before it played the Los Angeles Dodgers on 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, general manager Brian Cashman did his best to play  
down angry remarks made by acting manager Don Zimmer toward 
Steinbrenner a day earlier in connection with the Irabu episode. 
</P>
<P>
	``This isn't as big as it's been made into,'' Cashman said. ``I  
believe that yesterday was yesterday. Today is a new day, today is 
a day we get back to business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Through an interpreter, Irabu read a statement to Zimmer and his  
teammates apologizing for staying in Tampa. 
</P>
<P>
	Irabu, who has struggled this spring, said he asked to remain  
behind ``to think about many things.'' He didn't elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	Irabu also said he was going to try and regain the trust of his  
teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	When Irabu remained in Tampa, it was expected he would not  
rejoin the Yankees for several days, but that changed Saturday 
after several meetings and a one-hour workout at the Yankees' minor 
league facility. 
</P>
<P>
	At that stage, Steinbrenner said he hoped Irabu would pitch  
Wednesday in Oakland. But Zimmer, filling in for manager Joe Torre, 
had said Friday that Ramiro Mendoza would pitch against the A's 
instead. 
</P>
<P>
	Zimmer -- who wondered aloud ``who called him a fat pig, or a fat  
plum?'' -- said Saturday that his mind wouldn't be changed ``by 
anybody.'' He added that he would quit if given an ultimatum that 
Irabu would be Wednesday's starting pitcher. 
</P>
<P>
	``George Steinbrenner has been good to me, but, to me, you can't  
sit back here and be a little wimp,'' Zimmer said. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, the situation seemed quiet.  
</P>
<P>
	``I talked to the boss (Steinbrenner) this morning, and he said  
he didn't mandate that anyone start,'' Cashman said. ``This isn't 
as big as it's been made. There was certainly a bump in the road 
the last few days, there's no question. We've dealt with bigger 
things. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, like anybody, you don't want things blown up. I  
think it's fair to say you like to keep things in house.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When asked if Steinbrenner had expressed displeasure with  
Zimmer's remarks, Cashman replied, ``If he did, I prefer to keep 
that quiet. If he did, I'm not going to convey that to you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zimmer reiterated Sunday that Mendoza will pitch Wednesday, and  
that Irabu will be in the bullpen, at least for now. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was sorry the way things happened on Thursday,'' Zimmer  
said of Irabu. ``He felt that he embarrassed the whole club and he 
felt that he would have to win the respect back from the players. 
He seemed like he was very sincere. I would say that it's over 
with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zimmer said he thought it was important that Irabu speak with  
his teammates about the matter, and the apology wasn't solicited by 
anyone with the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Zimmer said Saturday he tried to phone Steinbrenner three  
different times, but was unable to make contact. He did talk with 
Torre, who asked how the acting manager was holding up -- Zimmer 
told him he was doing fine. 
</P>
<P>
	Torre underwent prostate cancer surgery last month, and no  
timetable has been set for his return, but Zimmer said he expects 
Torre to come back ``very soon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Irabu worked on covering first base while pitching coach Mel  
Stottlemyre threw batting practice. It was a drill that Zimmer said 
was supposed to take place Friday, but didn't since Irabu wasn't 
with the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Zimmer said Stottlemyre had conducted a similar drill previously  
with another pitcher. 
</P>
</TEXT>
