<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mormon Church To Rebuild Temple </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Mormon church President Gordon B. Hinckley  
chose Easter Sunday to announce the church will rebuild its 
historic Nauvoo Temple in Illinois, destroyed by arson and tornado 
after the Mormons moved West. 
</P>
<P>
	In his surprise disclosure at the end of the faith's 169th  
Annual General Conference, Hinckley said the rebuilt temple would 
stand as a memorial to those who built it. It was dedicated in 
1846, after most of the embattled Mormons had left to begin their 
massive exodus to the Salt Lake Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be a while before it happens, but the architects have  
begun their work,'' Hinckley said. ``This temple will not be busy 
much of the time. It will be somewhat isolated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he said it likely would be very busy during the summer  
months when thousands of members of The Church of Jesus Christ of 
Latter-day Saints visit Nauvoo, Ill. Portions of the city, once 
nearly equal to Chicago in population with some 15,000 residents, 
have been restored by the church. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nauvoo Temple, built on a bluff overlooking the Mississippi  
River on ground selected by church founder Joseph Smith, had an 
exterior of light gray limestone and a tower and spire 165 feet 
high. Smith laid the cornerstone in 1841, three years before he was 
assassinated by a mob in nearby Carthage, Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	Only the bare walls were left standing after the building was  
destroyed by an arson fire in October 1848. A tornado later knocked 
down some of the walls and much of the stone was later used in 
other buildings in the city. 
</P>
<P>
	Hinckley said a church member and his family -- he did not name  
them -- had made ``a very substantial contribution to make this 
possible. We are grateful to them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He did not say whether the restored temple would be built on the  
site of the old, where only foundation stones remain. The church 
already owns the site. 
</P>
<P>
	The church has 56 operating temples and 53 in various stages of  
planning and construction. Temples, where marriages and other 
ordinances considered sacred to Mormons are performed by worthy 
members, are distinct from chapels for weekly worship. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nauvoo Temple was the second built by the church. The first,  
in Kirtland, Ohio, was dedicated in 1836. The Mormons left Ohio and 
settled in Nauvoo in 1839. 
</P>
<P>
	Before his announcement, Hinckley called the 20th century both  
the bloodiest and best in history, an age of enlightenment marred 
by misery and conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has been the worst of all centuries with more of war, more  
of man's inhumanity to man, more of conflict and trouble than any 
other century in the history of the world,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The church president also returned to a theme he had sounded  
twice before during the two-day conference: Mormons need to shed 
what some outside the faith perceive as a ``holier-than-thou'' 
attitude. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can be a little more tolerant and friendly to those not of  
our faith, going out of our way to show our respect for them. We 
cannot afford to be arrogant or self-righteous,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
