<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> San Fran Court Going to the Dogs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Does your neighbor's dog howl at the moon  
until 2 a.m.? Did the pit bull next door eat your hamster? Is 
little Fifi sneaking into your yard and leaving unwanted deposits 
on your lawn? 
</P>
<P>
	Don't take the law into your own hands. Take those mutts to  
court -- Dog Court. 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, in San Francisco, justice is going to the dogs, thanks to  
police Sgt. William Herndon. He's a sort of Judge Judy for pooches 
who for the past five years has presided over Dog Court, where 
people with a bone to pick come to seek justice. 
</P>
<P>
	Herndon obviously loves dogs -- he has two -- and wants to protect  
owners' rights to their animals, as long as the city's human 
population isn't placed in jeopardy. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a very important job,'' he said before a recent  
session began. ``I want to do right for the people, for the dogs 
and make it safe for the city.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike a court for people, the dogs don't get to face their  
accusers. Instead, the folks on both sides of the issue show up, 
tell their stories -- with witnesses, if necessary -- and then, after 
a week or two, Herndon rules. 
</P>
<P>
	Occasionally an attorney shows up, but generally this is the  
most basic form of justice -- informal, casual, common sense. 
</P>
<P>
	His charter is a section of the city's health code, and the code  
says his word is final. In reality, owners can ask for a writ 
transferring the case to Superior Court, although that doesn't 
happen often. 
</P>
<P>
	Frequently, Herndon will order an alleged offender into the  
custody of the Department of Animal Care and Control for an 
evaluation by a canine behavioral expert. 
</P>
<P>
	Herndon, 45, heard three cases on a recent Thursday. The first  
two are fairly routine. In both, unleashed dogs bit other dogs, and 
Herndon tells the owners he will let them know his decision at a 
later date. 
</P>
<P>
	But the third case is serious. A young man named Sergio Guevara  
owns two pit bulls -- Buggsy and Cookie. Because of a broken-down 
fence, the dogs are able to get into a neighbor's yard. As Curtis 
Norman is shooing the dogs home, Buggsy jumps up and bites Norman's 
arm. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Norman seems willing to forgive and forget if Guevara  
fixes the fence, Arlene Norman, Curtis' wife, isn't as accepting. 
``I don't want to be attacked,'' she said with a scowl, mentioning 
visiting grandchildren. 
</P>
<P>
	Herndon tells Guevara to drop his dogs off at animal control by  
the end of the following day, so they can be examined by a 
behaviorist. He warns Guevara he won't get the dogs back until the 
fence is fixed. 
</P>
<P>
	Unfortunately, the story has a sad ending. While the dogs are  
being examined, Buggsy bites the behaviorist. Although the injury 
isn't severe, that's it for Buggsy -- a destruction order is issued. 
</P>
<P>
	The fate of Cookie, who didn't join the attack, was still to be  
determined. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 250 or so cases he's handled, one that sticks in  
Herndon's mind involved a 4-year-old girl who was playing with a 
stuffed animal when a dog belonging to her mother's boyfriend 
allegedly attacked, biting her in the scalp. When the mother got 
the dog off -- prying open its mouth with a broom handle -- she said 
it went back and bit her again. 
</P>
<P>
	``The mother said it was just an accident,'' Herndon said with a  
touch of disbelief in his voice. ``Even the little girl said it was 
an accident. The dog was destroyed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Does he handle any funny cases? Not many, apparently; he had to  
struggle to come up with the following: 
</P>
<P>
	``We had the case of a Jack Russell terrier who lived in a  
neighborhood where people left their doors open,'' he said. ``The 
dog got loose and ran into a neighbor's house, where he chased the 
people around. He didn't bite anybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But, said Herndon, that's classified as ``menacing behavior,'' a  
no-no under the city's health code. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
