<DOCNO> APW19990404.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 13:42:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fernandez Returns Against Mets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Coming back from the first serious injury of his  
career, Alex Fernandez knows better than to be greedy. He's 
delighted to start on opening day, and it's OK if he doesn't 
finish. 
</P>
<P>
	Fernandez, who sat out last season following rotator cuff  
surgery, returns to the mound Monday for the Florida Marlins 
against former teammate Al Leiter and the New York Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	The Marlins will limit Fernandez to about 100 pitches, and  
that's fine with him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like if I go out there for five or six innings, I've  
done my job, at least for now,'' he said. ``It's a long haul. It's 
not Game 7 of the World Series. I'm 29 years old, and I've got a 
lot of pitching ahead of me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's not the World Series, but it will be Fernandez's first game  
since the 1997 National League championship series, when his 
career-threatening injury was diagnosed. He went 17-12 for the 
World Series champs, then spent last year on the disabled list 
while Florida plunged from first to last, losing 108 games. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the Marlins have a new manager in John Boles and a new owner  
in John Henry, who bought the team last winter from Wayne Huizenga. 
Florida's goal this year is merely to begin the long climb toward 
contention -- or at least .500. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets, meanwhile, went on a spending spree during the winter  
and hope to make the playoffs for the first time since 1988. New 
York newcomers include Robin Ventura, Rickey Henderson and Bobby 
Bonilla, who is beginning his second stint with the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Leiter will make his first start in Miami since Game 7 of the  
1997 World Series, when he helped the Marlins beat the Cleveland 
Indians. The opening day assignment is his first. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an honor,'' said Leiter, who has a home 20 minutes from  
Pro Player Stadium. ``My family and friends will be there. A lot 
will be going on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, his first year with the Mets, Leiter went 17-6 with a  
2.47 ERA. The veteran left-hander struggled to an 0-4 record with a 
5.84 ERA in spring training. 
</P>
<P>
	``Stuff-wise I feel fine,'' he said. ``I'm ready.''  
</P>
<P>
	Fernandez shares that attitude. With three seasons remaining on  
a contract that pays $7 million a year, Fernandez could provide a 
foundation for Florida's future. Or he could become trade bait. 
Either way, he was encouraged by his performance in spring 
training. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were no setbacks,'' he said. ``I was able to make every  
start. I'm pretty pleased.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fernandez went 0-1 with a 4.32 ERA in six games, and his  
fastball clocked at 90 mph, the norm before his injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes his command isn't in midseason form, but his  
velocity is where it was in the past,'' Boles said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fernandez will match pitches in the opener with Leiter, who went  
27-21 for Florida in 1996-97, including a no-hitter. 
</P>
<P>
	``What a coincidence I've got to face Leiter,'' Fernandez said.  
``It'll be fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year wasn't a total loss for Fernandez -- in October, he and  
his wife had their fourth child. Young Andrew provides a welcome 
diversion as Fernandez braces for an emotional return to the mound. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've tried stay away from thinking about that,'' he said. ``I  
want to worry about doing what I need to do to be ready. The 
emotions are going to carry themselves when I walk out there. 
</P>
<P>
	``And when you're changing three diapers a day, you don't think  
about that stuff.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
