<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teacher, Wife in Rebel Standoff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) -- The high school says the teacher was  
fired for cause. The teacher says he lost his job for defending the 
``Lost Cause.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For months, St. Joseph's High School headmaster Paul Leonarczyk  
asked Winston McCuen to move a 22-square-inch Confederate battle 
flag to a less conspicuous spot in his classroom. 
</P>
<P>
	After the parents of two prospective students ``expressed  
vehement offense'' at the flag, Leonarczyk took it down himself and 
put it in McCuen's desk. 
</P>
<P>
	In response to this perceived affront to his Southern heritage,  
McCuen refused to stand for the Pledge of Allegiance at assembly. 
He was fired Jan. 22. 
</P>
<P>
	McCuen says he thought his views would be embraced at a  
conservative, Christian school in a state that still proudly flies 
the battle flag atop its capitol. As part of a growing Southern 
separatist movement, he isn't about to sell out his rebel 
ancestors. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd rather keep my soul than keep my job,'' says McCuen, 37,  
sitting in Tommy's Country Ham House beneath portraits of 
Confederate generals Robert E. Lee and Thomas ``Stonewall'' 
Jackson. 
</P>
<P>
	The League of the South, a Southern nationalist group, has  
declared McCuen's firing a ``heritage violation'' and has called on 
all good ``Southrons'' to offer financial and moral support. The 
Southern Legal Resource Center is preparing a lawsuit on his 
behalf. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just sorry that rampant political correctness seems to  
rule the roost these days,'' says Kirk Lyons of Black Mountain, 
N.C., the group's chief trial counsel. ``At some point, the people 
in South Carolina and Greenvile and the South in general are going 
to have to stand up and say, `We're sick of it.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Most important to McCuen is the support of his wife, Carmen,  
whom he calls a ``true Confederate lady.'' She backs his decision, 
even though his stance leaves the couple without steady income less 
than two months before the birth of their first child. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would be much more worried if he had done the wrong thing,  
and our child had found out about it and had to be ashamed of what 
his father did,'' she says, touching her husband affectionately on 
the shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	Both McCuens have ancestors who fought for the Confederacy. On  
the walls of their living room hang portraits of Lee and states' 
rights champion John C. Calhoun of South Carolina, as well as a 
picture of war-ravaged -- but fictional -- Tara from ``Gone With the 
Wind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We're culturally different; we're culturally distinct,'' Mrs.  
McCuen, 25, says of Southerners. ``It's a past that's not to be 
ashamed of. It's a past to be proud of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Winston McCuen let St. Joseph's know up front about his  
secessionist beliefs but promised his politics would not color the 
way he taught history, government and Latin. As part of his 
contract negotiations last summer, McCuen agreed to stand for the 
pledge, provided he could substitute the phrase, ``... one nation, 
under God, divisible ...'' 
</P>
<P>
	To a classroom array of Latin posters and pull-down maps, McCuen  
added his own touches: a print of George Washington praying at 
Valley Forge; a portrait of Calhoun, the subject of McCuen's 
doctoral thesis; a 3-by-5-foot Betsy Ross flag; and the Confederate 
battle flag, which hung in a corner visible from the classroom 
door. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what all the fuss is about,'' he says, fishing the  
small piece of cloth from the back seat of his car. ``A bandana.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leonarczyk spoke with McCuen about the flag several times over  
five months. 
</P>
<P>
	``During these lengthy discussions, I first attempted to  
understand your perspective and to appreciate your conviction about 
it,'' he wrote in a memo to McCuen. 
</P>
<P>
	McCuen insists the flag was a ``teaching aid,'' much like the  
Israeli banner on the wall in a neighboring classroom. But 
Leonarczyk, in the memo, said the ``singular placement and display 
of the Confederate flag made it not a teaching tool, but a symbol 
that many find offensive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When two parents complained about the flag after an open house,  
Leonarczyk removed it. When McCuen refused to stand for the Pledge 
the next day, some students took notice and followed suit. 
Leonarczyk says McCuen's decision to discuss the issue with his 
students was ``unprofessional.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leonarczyk declined comment because of the threatened lawsuit.  
</P>
<P>
	The school's attorneys say St. Joseph's was within its rights to  
dismiss McCuen and have refused a request to reinstate him. St. 
Joseph's has also contested his claim for unemployment benefits, 
McCuen says. 
</P>
<P>
	Lyons says the case goes beyond one man's firing.  
</P>
<P>
	``The issue here is, I think, there really is an ethnic  
cleansing of Confederate symbols throughout the South,'' says 
Lyons, founder of the CAUSE Foundation, which stands for Canada, 
Australia, United States, South Africa and Europe -- areas where 
Lyons considers the civil liberties of right-wing groups and 
individuals to be endangered. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, McCuen is making do by substitute teaching in the  
public school system. Mrs. McCuen took mandatory maternity leave 
from Furman University on Feb. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	In his memo, Leonarczyk practically pleaded with McCuen to  
``consider as your first priority your responsibility to your wife 
and future son.'' McCuen says that's just what he's doing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want my son and my wife and my family to respect their  
father and husband,'' he says. ``And if I knuckle under -- if I gave 
in -- they won't. So that means you've got to stand up for 
something.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
