<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 13:33:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McGwire Takes Aim at His Own Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Mark McGwire is back at 0.  
</P>
<P>
	Now it's time to see if he can begin the way he did last year,  
when he hit an opening-day grand slam off Ramon Martinez in a 6-0 
win over the Dodgers, the first of his record 70 home runs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure no matter what I do this year. if I don't hit 70  
someone will say I had an off year,'' McGwire said as the St. Louis 
Cardinals prepared for Monday night's opener against the Milwaukee 
Brewers. 
</P>
<P>
	St. Louis already has sold 2.5 million tickets -- even a couple  
hundred season tickets in the prime home-run territory out in left 
-- with fans anticipating more McGwire moon shots. 
</P>
<P>
	His career best 545-foot homer, the longest ever at Busch  
Stadium, slammed off a sign beyond the center-field backdrop that's 
now memorialized by a huge band-aid. He homered in each of the 
first four games to tie Willie Mays' major league record and 
eclipsed Roger Maris' old record of 61 with three weeks to spare. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, there's also the chase for 500. McGwire needs 43  
homers to become the 16th player in major league history to reach 
that barrier. And he could become the first player to hit 50 or 
more in four consecutive years. 
</P>
<P>
	If he hits 50, some will be disappointed.  
</P>
<P>
	``That's still a very good number,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	McGwire's heroics last season enabled the Cardinals to draw 3.2  
million fans even though they were 19 games back in the NL Central 
and finished 83-79. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, the team doesn't figure to be much better. The No. 1  
starter is the often-injured Donovan Osborne, who has eight 
victories the last two seasons. Center fielder Ray Lankford, who 
hits cleanup behind McGwire, and shortstop Edgar Renteria still are 
recovering from injuries sustained last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Renteria, who had a bone bruise in his right knee, has a good  
shot of starting the opener although he likely won't be stealing 
bases for a while. Renteria played Sunday in a short scrimmage 
against Fontbonne College that served as the last spring outing for 
No. 4 starter Darren Oliver. 
</P>
<P>
	``It feels good,'' Renteria said. ``We worked hard to get ready.  
I'm excited.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lankford, who had surgery in November to repair torn tendons in  
his left knee, likely will be placed on the 15-day disabled list. 
One of the infield backups, David Howard, injured his groin on 
Sunday and likely will go on the DL as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Milwaukee starts rookie left-hander Rafael Roque, who allowed  
home runs No. 64 to both McGwire and Sammy Sosa. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I learned something by facing both McGwire and Sosa  
last year, so I may do some things different,'' Roque said. ``I 
want to get on TV because I'm doing my job, not from giving up home 
runs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roque, who will be making only his 10th career start in the  
opener, scooted from No. 4 starter to No. 1 after Scott Karl went 
0-2 with a 7.20 ERA in four spring starts. Manager Phil Garner was 
reluctant to elevate his top pitcher, Steve Woodard, because of the 
pressure that goes with being No. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Along with Renteria, other new faces with the Cardinals are  
heralded rookie J.D. Drew, who'll bat second in front of McGwire, 
and Eric Davis, who'll probably bat cleanup until Lankford is 
ready. 
</P>
<P>
	The top newcomers to the Brewers, seeking to end six straight  
losing seasons, are left-hander Jim Abbott and first baseman Sean 
Berry. 
</P>
<P>
	The opening three-game series has two interesting subplots. The  
Cardinals are still trying to make a deal for disgruntled Brewers 
second baseman Fernando Vina, with the holdup so far St. Louis' 
reluctance to part with promising right-hander Jose Jimenez. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not the GM, but I certainly don't think we'll trade him,''  
Cardinals pitching coach Dave Duncan. 
</P>
<P>
	The second wrinkle is whether Cardinals manager Tony La Russa  
continues to bat his pitcher eighth. He said Sunday that Osborne 
will bat ninth in the opener. St. Louis was 46-36 last year with 
the pitcher hitting eighth. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's there if it ever makes sense,'' La Russa said, ``but I  
don't think we need to do it tomorrow.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
