<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Expos-Pirates in Low-Wage Opener  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The Montreal Expos and Pittsburgh Pirates have  
something in common other than minimum-wage payrolls, cavernous 
stadiums and a shared belief they can be the NL's surprise team 
this season. 
</P>
<P>
	It's called opening day.  
</P>
<P>
	They no longer play in the same division and they haven't had  
much of a rivalry since the 1970s. No matter, the NL schedule maker 
still keeps matching them on opening day. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pirates' Francisco Cordova (13-14, 3.31 ERA) opposes the  
Expos' Dustin Hermanson (14-11, 3.13 ERA) in a sold-out Three 
Rivers Stadium Monday night in the second Pirates-Expos opener in 
as many seasons. It also will be the sixth time in 11 years the 
Pirates have opened at home with Montreal. 
</P>
<P>
	Parlez-vous francais, Pittsburgh?  
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, you don't care who you play, you just want to start  
playing,'' first baseman Kevin Young said. ``It's time to jet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Pirates beat the Expos 4-0 behind Cordova on opening day  
last season, but won only 68 more times amid a disappointing year 
that saw them lose 25 of their final 30. The Expos were even worse, 
going 65-97 with the majors' smallest payroll. 
</P>
<P>
	Call it the eternal optimism that abounds every spring, even in  
an era when finances are dividing baseball into the haves and 
have-nots. But the Expos and Pirates are convinced 1998 was a 
stepping stone to a better future, not a step backward. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pirates' late-season collapse convinced general manager Cam  
Bonifay to augment a youth-driven rebuilding project with 
experience, and he brought in five new position players. 
</P>
<P>
	Four will start Monday: left fielder Brian Giles, center fielder  
Brant Brown, third baseman Ed Sprague and shortstop Mike Benjamin. 
Shortstop Pat Meares also would have started, but is out with a 
sprained left wrist. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, rookie second baseman Warren Morris makes the leap from  
Double-A to the majors after hitting four homers during the 
Pirates' first winning spring since 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	The makeover means the Pirates will no longer do their  
on-the-job training on the major league level (third baseman Aramis 
Ramirez started last season at age 19). It also has created more 
optimism since the Pirates last won a division title in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Is it false optimism? The Pirates are convinced it's not.  
</P>
<P>
	With good starting pitching, an upgraded defense and more  
leadership, they believe they can sneak up in a division where no 
team has a competition-busting $85 million payroll like the Yankees 
do. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a chance to be real, real good if we perform up to our  
capabilities,'' Bonifay said. 
</P>
<P>
	They have a chance for a quick getaway. They start the season  
with a nine-game homestand, including three games each against the 
NL Central rivals Chicago and St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	The Expos' optimism, as always, results from a farm system that  
keeps turning out excellent prospects almost as fast as they can 
leave for organizations that can afford them. 
</P>
<P>
	Right fielder Vladimir Guerrero (.324, 38 homers, 109 RBIs)  
certainly is a keeper, the cornerstone of the franchise and a 
player who might be only one more big year away from being regarded 
as the NL's best overall player. 
</P>
<P>
	Center fielder Rondell White was on track for a 30 homers-30  
steals year until breaking a finger in June. First baseman Brad 
Fullmer had 44 doubles as a rookie. Ugeth Urbina is an excellent 
closer who might have even more save opportunities if the Expos had 
better middle relief. 
</P>
<P>
	Hermanson could become the Expos' first 20-game winner since  
Ross Grimsley in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've going to surprise a lot of people,'' said Hermanson, who  
tuned up for Monday's start with five strong innings Wednesday 
against the Cardinals. 
</P>
<P>
	The surprise would be if the Expos, who will pay their 25-man  
roster slightly less than the $15 million average annual salary of 
the Dodgers' Kevin Brown, can stay in contention in the NL East 
alongside big spenders Atlanta and the New York Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got a lot of talent,'' said manager Felipe Alou, who  
turned down the Dodgers so he could finish out the Expos' seemingly 
endless rebuilding project. 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* Meares still hopes to be ready by Friday. ... The sellout  
is the Pirates' third in a row on opening day. ... The Pirates were 
7-2 against Montreal last season. ... The combined 134 victories by 
the Expos and Pirates last season were only nine more than the 
Yankees had by themselves in the regular and postseason. ... 
Cordova was 2-0 with a 1.29 ERA against Montreal last season. ... 
Wednesday's game was moved to an afternoon start so the Pirates can 
break ground that evening on PNC Park, which will open in 2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
