<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                           *David Brooks    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- David Brooks, an actor, director and producer  
who starred in the leading role of Tommy Albright in the Broadway 
musical ``Brigadoon,'' died Wednesday. He was 83. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks debuted on Broadway in 1945 in the musical comedy  
``Bloomer Girl.'' In 1947, Brooks landed the role in Brigadoon, a 
musical by Alan Jay Lerner and Frederick Loewe that went on to play 
581 performances. 
</P>
<P>
	He directed and produced in Italy in the 1950s, and in the U.S.  
helped set up Rooftop Productions, which was behind the American 
premieres of James Joyce's ``Ulysses in Nighttown'' and Samuel 
Beckett's ``Endgame.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks was born in Portland, Ore., and graduated from the  
University of Washington. He studied opera at the Curtis Institute 
of Music in Philadelphia. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Peter J. Pitchess    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Peter J. Pitchess, who as county sheriff for  
23 years made the department into one of the nation's largest, died 
Sunday at home. He was 87. 
</P>
<P>
	Pitchess, appointed sheriff in 1958, saw the department expand  
into the nation's sixth largest police agency. It now includes more 
than 8,000 deputies, is responsible for policing 2.5 million 
people, and operates a 19,000-inmate jail system. 
</P>
<P>
	He retired in 1982.  
</P>
<P>
	Before joining the sheriff's department in 1953, Pitchess worked  
as an FBI agent and for the Atlantic Richfield Oil Co. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by his wife, Athena, and two sons.  

</P>
<P>
                            *Ray F. Mack    	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ray F. Mack, a former president and business  
manager of the former Washington Daily News, died April 2 of 
complications from diabetes. He was 86. 
</P>
<P>
	Mack was a past president and director of the International  
Circulation Managers Association and a past member of the board of 
review of the Audit Bureau of Circulations. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Daily News was sold by Scripps-Howard Newspapers in  
1972, Mack became assistant to the general business manager of 
Scripps-Howard and then its assistant business manager from 1975 
until retiring in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife, Betty, a daughter and two  
granddaughters. 

</P>
<P>
                     *Alfonso Sanchez Madariaga    	
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Alfonso Sanchez Madariaga, a founder of  
Mexico's dominant labor movement, died Saturday of a heart attack. 
He was 94. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanchez was one of the ``five wolf cubs,'' young labor leaders  
who split with the then-dominant labor federation in 1929 and laid 
the groundwork for what became the Mexican Labor Confederation, or 
CTM. 
</P>
<P>
	The CTM still dominates Mexico's labor movement today.  
</P>
<P>
	He remained active in the confederation as well as the Mexican  
Social Security Institute throughout his life. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanchez, born in Mexico City, began his labor career when he  
helped form a milkman's union there in 1924. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanchez was twice a senator from Mexico City, once serving as  
Senate president. He was also a federal congressman for two terms. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by his widow and five children.  

</P>
<P>
                            *Irene Samuel    	
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Irene Samuel, who fought to reopen  
Little Rock public schools after they were closed to prevent 
desegregation, died Saturday. She was 84. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1958, Gov. Orval E. Faubus and the Legislature called a  
special election that closed schools to prevent further 
desegregation. Ms. Samuel was one of 58 women who formed the 
Women's Emergency Committee to Open Our Schools. She became unpaid 
executive secretary and chief strategist for the group. 
</P>
<P>
	Schools re-opened a year later, and Ms. Samuel worked  
unsuccessfully to get Faubus out of office. He served three more 
terms, choosing not to seek re-election in 1966. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1970, she helped Dale Bumpers get elected governor, and  
served as his administrative assistant in Little Rock and during 
the first of his four U.S. Senate terms. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Samuel grew up in Little Rock, a daughter of a railroad  
switchman, and after graduating in 1931 worked for the federal 
Public Housing Authority in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1939, she moved back to Little Rock and married Dr. John  
Samuel, a surgeon. Their son was in grade school when the Little 
Rock desegregation crisis broke out. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Robert Webb    	
</P>
<P>
	BREMERTON, Wash. (AP) -- Robert E. Webb, believed to be the  
Navy's oldest retired chief petty officer, died Thursday at age 
100. 
</P>
<P>
	Webb, a native of Greenville, Miss., whose grandparents were  
slaves, served in World Wars I and II and was chief steward for six 
admirals. 
</P>
<P>
	Webb was working in a rubber plant in Akron, Ohio, when a Navy  
poster caught his eye in 1918 and he enlisted. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hadn't seen nothing but the Mississippi River,'' he said in  
an interview last May. 
</P>
<P>
	While stationed in France in World War I, he survived the  
sinking of his boat in a German attack. After the war ended, Webb 
became a cook and went on to prepare food for dignitaries and 
diplomats from around the world. In the 1930s, he served aboard the 
historic sailing ship USS Constitution. 
</P>
<P>
	His service took him around the world three times and he  
attained the rank of master chief, an almost unheard-of 
accomplishment for blacks before the military was desegregated. 
</P>
<P>
	He settled in Bremerton, where he married in 1944. Three years  
later he left the military and took a civilian job at the Puget 
Sound Naval Shipyard. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include a daughter and two grandchildren.  
</P>
</TEXT>
