<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Eight inmates were shot and killed in a  
high-security Bogota prison in what was believed to be a settling 
of scores between two rival gangs, authorities said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The killings occurred during an hourlong melee that broke out  
Saturday night in one of the eight cellblocks at La Modelo prison, 
an overcrowded penitentiary that holds some 3,800 inmates, 
authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	The prison's director, Liliana Obregon, told reporters the  
killings were still under investigation. She said it was not known 
how the weapons used had entered the prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite searches that Obregon said are routine for anyone  
entering La Modelo, guns and knives -- along with virtually anything 
else -- are frequently smuggled into even Colombia's highest 
security prisons. Poorly paid prison guards are highly susceptible 
to bribes. 
</P>
<P>
	The victims had been imprisoned for crimes including armed  
robbery and theft, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- The Dalai Lama arrived in Brazil  
on Sunday, saying he was optimistic about the situation of Tibet in 
China. 
</P>
<P>
	``In spite of all the sadness, I think that things are changing  
for the better,'' the exiled Tibetan spiritual leader told 
reporters, on his second trip to Brazil since a 1992 conference on 
the environment. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dalai Lama, who has pressed China for Tibetan autonomy but  
not outright independence, wore the customary scarlet robe of a 
Buddhist monk. He was met by flower-bearing followers at his first 
stop in Curitiba, located 500 miles south of Rio de Janeiro. 
</P>
<P>
	During his four-day visit, the 63-year-old spiritual leader  
participate in seminars and speeches and meet religious figures, 
politicians and artists in Curitiba and the capital, Brasilia, 
where he will also address the Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	In his honor, samba superstars Gilberto Gil and Elba Ramalho  
will perform a special concert Monday night in Curitiba. 
``Kundun,'' a 1996 Hollywood film about his life, will finally make 
its Brazilian premiere on April 9. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- A severe drought in northeast  
Brazil caused infant mortality to increase slightly last year, 
according to a health ministry report published Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The report shows that 32,407 infants nationwide -- 12,019 in the  
northeast -- died last year, up from 31,602 in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Alagoas, a northeastern sugar growing state, led the nation with  
a rate of 86.8 deaths per 1,000 births, double the national 
average. 
</P>
<P>
	Most deaths are due to malnutrition, respiratory infections and  
diarrhea, said the report published in the Folha de Sao Paulo 
newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	The northeast, an arid region larger than any country in Western  
Europe, experiences a major drought every dozen years or so. In the 
early 1980s, more than 350,000 people died in a prolonged drought, 
and malnutrition affects 40 percent of the area's children. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A moderate eruption shook the crater of the  
Popocatepetl volcano early Sunday, but officials said it quickly 
calmed. 
</P>
<P>
	The explosion appears to be one in a series over recent months  
that seismologists believe has released pressure as it builds up 
within the 17,925-foot mountain, some 40 miles southeast of Mexico 
City. 
</P>
<P>
	The explosion just before dawn was heard by people in San Andres  
Calpan, about 12 miles from the crater, according to the National 
Center for the Prevention of Disasters. 
</P>
<P>
	Witnesses said they saw a glow over the crater.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Luis M. Farias, a founder of Mexico's radio  
announcers union who served a governor and senator, has died at 78, 
newspapers reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Farias died Saturday while vacationing with his family at  
Cocoyoc, south of Mexico City. The cause of death was not reported, 
but he had suffered from Parkinson's disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Farias was born in Monterrey on June 7, 1920, and went on to  
earn a law degree from the National Autonomous University in Mexico 
City. 
</P>
<P>
	He worked as a radio announcer for what was then Mexico's top  
radio station, XEW, and formed a union there. He later helped found 
a national union of broadcasters. 
</P>
<P>
	He joined the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party and  
served as governor of his native Nuevo Leon state from 1970 to 
1973. He was a federal congressman for three terms -- 1955-58, 
1967-70 and 1979-82, as well as senator in 1970 and from 1973 to 
1976. 
</P>
</TEXT>
