<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Wraps Up Search at Texas Ranch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP WOOD, Texas (AP) -- The FBI on Sunday wrapped up a three-day  
search at a south Texas cattle ranch for clues to the disappearance 
of atheist leader Madalyn Murray O'Hair, but declined to say 
whether they found anything. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am not going to comment on whether we gathered evidence or  
not,'' Robert Grant, assistant special agent in charge of the FBI's 
San Antonio office, said Sunday. ``We came here to find evidence 
and we'll leave it at that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI has refused to confirm the subject of the investigation,  
but the Texas Department of Public Safety said Saturday it was 
helping federal agents in a search for evidence in the 1995 
disappearance of Mrs. O'Hair; her son, Jon Garth Murray; 
granddaughter, Robin Murray O'Hair; and $500,000 in gold coins. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are assisting the FBI, searching for evidence related to  
the Madalyn Murray O'Hair case,'' said DPS spokesman Tom Vinger. 
``That doesn't mean they're looking for bodies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI used dogs, heavy equipment including a backhoe and a  
helicopter with night vision to search about 1,000 acres of the 
5,000-acre Cooksy Ranch, about 100 miles west of San Antonio in 
Real County. The U.S. Attorney's office said the ranch owners were 
not targets of the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. O'Hair's 1963 Supreme Court case led to the ban on  
organized prayer in public schools. She founded American Atheists 
Inc., a nonprofit group dedicated to the separation of church and 
state which was based for many years in Austin. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, David R. Waters, 52, the former office manager for  
Mrs. O'Hair, and Gary P. Karr, 50, were arrested on weapons 
charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Waters has denied involvement in the O'Hairs' disappearance, and  
neither man has been charged in connection with the case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
