<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Albright Takes Aim at Milosevic  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright today  
blamed the burgeoning refugee crisis in the Balkans on Yugoslav 
President Slobodan Milosevic, whose forces have continued attacks 
on ethnic Albanian and forced them out of Kosovo. Albright, 
appearing on NBC, dismissed the suggestion that the NATO air 
campaign led to the crisis. Meanwhile a Pentagon spokesman said it 
was ``encouraging'' that the Yugoslav government will treat three 
captured U.S. soldiers as prisoners-of-war, which could protect 
them from trial. 

</P>
<P>
	Belgrade Prepares For More Attacks  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Air raid sirens sounded tonight in  
Belgrade, signaling the start of a 12th night of NATO airstrikes on 
Yugoslavia, as NATO warplanes and missiles pounded targets in and 
around the city earlier in the day. The Tanjug state news agency 
said that NATO attacks on an oil refinery at Pancevo, northeast of 
Belgrade, killed two workers and injured four, while a 73-year-old 
woman died and seven people were injured in an attack on Cacak, an 
industrial town 50 miles south of the capital. Three people were 
injured when a fuel depot near the town of Kraljevo, some 75 miles 
south of Belgrade, was also hit, Yugoslav news reports said. 

</P>
<P>
	Lockerbie Suspects' Trial Nears  
</P>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Arab and African dignitaries began arriving  
in Libya today to witness the handover of two suspects in the 1988 
Pan Am bombing, signaling that their extradition is imminent. The 
convergence of officials followed reports that the chief U.N. legal 
counsel, Hans Corell, had left for Europe on Friday on his way to 
Libya to arrange the handover. Lamen Khalifa Fhimah, 42 and Abdel 
Basset Ali al-Megrahi, 46, are to be tried under Scottish law in 
the Netherlands. The bombing killed 270 people, mostly Americans 
and Britons 

</P>
<P>
	Mormon Church To Rebuild Temple  
</P>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- In a surprise disclosure, Mormon church  
President Gordon B. Hinckley today said the church will rebuild its 
historic Nauvoo Temple in Illinois, destroyed by arson and tornado 
after the Mormons moved West. The temple was dedicated in 1846 
after most of the embattled Mormons had left for the Salt Lake 
Valley and destroyed in an arson fire two years later. Hinckley 
made the announcement at the end of the faith's 169th Annual 
General Conference. 

</P>
<P>
	Profits Dip at Fortune 500 Firms  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- According to Fortune magazine's annual listing  
of the largest U.S. public companies, profits at the Fortune 500 
companies declined for the first time in seven years in 1998. U.S. 
companies suffered the effects of the economic crisis in Asia, 
Russia and Latin America, as profits for the 500 fell 1.8 percent 
last year, compared to 7.8 percent earnings growth in 1997. GM 
topped the list for the 11th year straight, taking in $161.3 
billion in 1998. 

</P>
<P>
	Va. Shipbuilding Union Plans Strike  
</P>
<P>
	NEWPORT NEWS, Va. (AP) -- Thousands of workers were scheduled to  
begin striking at Newport News Shipbuilding when their contract 
expires at midnight. The union, which represents many of the yard's 
9,200 hourly workers, planned to strike over what it says are 
insufficient raises in a proposed new contract. In the new 
contract, the union wants an across-the-board hourly pay increase 
of $3.95 over three years. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Attacks Gore on Internet Claim  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Seizing on Vice Al Gore's visit to Silicon  
Valley this week to raise campaign money, a Republican group has 
created a bruising television commercial that ridicules him for 
taking the lead in creating the Internet. The advertisement, 
financed by the Republican Leadership Council, also rips Gore's 
claim for having worked on reinventing government, a major project 
during the Clinton administration. A group spokesman said the ad 
will run over 50 times in two days in the area around Silicon 
Valley, including on broadcast stations in San Francisco, at a cost 
of roughly $30,000. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Up After Survey  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rose early Monday after the central  
bank said business confidence at Japan's recession-hit 
manufacturers improved. The Nikkei climbed 188.73 points to 
16,478.92 in early trading. 

</P>
<P>
	Raptors Beat 76ers, 97-82  
</P>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Doug Christie scored 22 points and rookie Vince  
Carter had 20 tonight as the Toronto Raptors trounced the 
Philadelphia 76ers 97-82 and set a club record with their sixth 
straight win. The Raptors moved into seventh place the Eastern 
Conference, a half-game ahead of the New York Knicks. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  


</P>
