<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-04 13:42:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vaughn Is Star for Reds' Opener </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Greg Vaughn has only a vague recollection of  
his first opening day in Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were a lot of people. It was a little cold. I don't  
remember too much else,'' Vaughn said, thinking back to one year 
ago. ``I remember the elephants pooping all over the place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reds fans are hoping Vaughn gives them more pleasant memories on  
Monday afternoon. Elephants again will parade during pregame 
festivities, but Vaughn will be the star attraction when the Reds 
take the field in new uniforms and facial hair -- one change 
prompted by Vaughn -- to play San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, another California team -- the San Diego Padres -- came  
to Cincinnati and got a 10-2 win that launched one of the best 
seasons in franchise history. 
</P>
<P>
	Vaughn was the only Padres starter who didn't have a hit that  
day. He got to make it two Cincinnati openers in a row when the 
Padres traded him to the Reds for Reggie Sanders on Feb. 2. 
</P>
<P>
	Due in large part to that trade, the opener sold out faster than  
it had in six years and Reds fans are talking about playoff 
possibilities. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fans are getting excited about it and they should be,''  
pitcher Denny Neagle said Sunday before a workout at Cinergy Field. 
``We said all spring training we feel we have a special team here 
that can do something this year. Hopefully, we can go out there and 
put on a good show.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year's opener was the Reds' worst showing in a generation.  
Pokey Reese made four errors, tying the record for a shortstop on 
opening day, and the eight-run loss was their most lopsided 
opening-day defeat in 36 years. 
</P>
<P>
	That loss came only a few hours after the Reds traded their No.  
1 starter, Dave Burba, to Cleveland, a move that told fans there 
was no reason to hope for the playoffs. After the game, owner Marge 
Schott fell in the driveway of her home and broke her hip. 
</P>
<P>
	Vaughn may have the best chance to point this opener in a  
different direction. Vaughn is 5-for-13 career against Giants 
starter Mark Gardner (13-6), and all five hits have been homers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't pay attention to whether I've had success against  
somebody or not,'' Vaughn said. ``If I've got a bat in my hand, 
I've got a chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brett Tomko, the Reds' No. 3 pitcher when spring training began,  
will make his first opening day start because Neagle is on the 
disabled list with shoulder weakness and Pete Harnisch has been 
slowed by a bad back. 
</P>
<P>
	Tomko (13-12) figures it will be much like last Aug. 6, when he  
started before a capacity crowd in St. Louis and kept Mark McGwire 
stuck on 60 homers for one more day. 
</P>
<P>
	``I pitched in that game when he was about to break the record.  
That was a pretty intense thing,'' Tomko said Sunday. ``I imagine 
it will be kind of the same feeling, the same atmosphere -- except 
the crowd will be rooting for me, hopefully.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Giants are looking to follow the Padres' example and get a  
good feeling about themselves from Day 1. San Francisco came as 
close as possible to making the playoffs last season, losing a 
one-game playoff to the Chicago Cubs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe from the bottom of my heart that this is supposed to  
be our year,'' manager Dusty Baker said. ``No explanation. I just 
feel it. I just think we've got a lot of things going in our 
favor.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
