<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S. To Send Helicopters to Albania  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon has agreed to send 24 Apache  
helicopter gunships and 2,000 troops to Albania, deepening 
America's military commitment in the Balkans. The Clinton 
administration said today that the Apaches would give NATO the 
ability to directly attack Serb soldiers and tanks in Yugoslavia. 
Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said deploying the Apaches was ``a 
logical expansion'' of the nearly two-week-old NATO airstrikes to 
halt Yugoslav Slobodan Milosevic's military drive against ethnic 
Albanians in the Serbian province of Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers Urge Use of Troops  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., today said it was  
time for Congress to consider a vote on the use of U.S. ground 
troops in Kosovo. He joined several other lawmakers from both 
parties in urging President Clinton not to rule out the option of 
sending combat forces into the Serbian province. The 
no-ground-troops stand only emboldens Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic into pressing his attack against ethnic Albanians, 
lawmakers said. 

</P>
<P>
	Thousands Hold Rally in Montenegro  
</P>
<P>
	PODGORICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- In a show of anger at NATO, some  
10,000 Montenegrins jammed a central square in their capital 
tonight to protest the alliance's air strikes on the region. The 
peaceful demonstration marked the biggest outpouring yet of 
anti-NATO sentiment in the tense Yugoslav republic. Montenegro's 
pro-Western authorities stepped up security around key buildings 
out of fear an eruption of violence could spark attacks on their 
government. 

</P>
<P>
	Six Killed in Louisiana Tornado  
</P>
<P>
	BENTON, La. (AP) -- Searchers this morning combed through piles  
of wreckage in the hopes of finding more survivors of a twister 
that ripped through Bossier Parish and killed six people yesterday. 
The tornado, believed to be about a half-mile wide, curved through 
farm and rural land, hitting two mobile home parks in this 
northwest Louisiana community as well as the upscale subdivision of 
Palmetto Park. A separate tornado destroyed a church southwest of 
Shreveport near the Texas border. 

</P>
<P>
	Easter Violence Erupts in Nazareth  
</P>
<P>
	NAZARETH, Israel (AP) -- Clashes erupted today between Christians  
and Muslims who are upset about the planned construction of a plaza 
for millennium pilgrims near a mosque. More than 70 Israeli police 
wearing riot gear were called into quell the Easter Sunday violence 
in the town of Jesus' boyhood. Thousands of young Muslim men 
gathered near the Church of the Annunciation, insulting Christian 
worshippers. Other youths, wielding clubs, smashed windshields of 
parked cars with crosses dangling from the mirrors. 

</P>
<P>
	Profits for Fortune 500 Firms Dip  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Profits at the Fortune 500 companies declined  
for the first time in seven years in 1998 as the economic crisis in 
Asia, Russia and Latin America took its toll on U.S. firms. Profits 
fell 1.8 percent last year, compared to 7.8 percent earnings growth 
in 1997, according to Fortune magazine's annual listing of the 
largest U.S. public companies. Revenue growth shrank to 4 percent 
from 8.7 percent in 1997 as U.S. companies found demand for their 
products and services stifled by the ongoing financial problems 
overseas. General Motors remained No. 1 for the 11th straight year 
on Fortune's list, which ranks companies according to revenue. 

</P>
<P>
	Slow Sales for Diana Museum Tickets  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Sales of tickets to visit Princess Diana's  
ancestral home and her final resting place have been slow so far 
this year, and nearly half remain unsold three months before the 
gates are opened to the public. Diana's brother, Earl Spencer, will 
open the Althorp estate, and the museum he created in her memory, 
from July 1 through Aug. 30, the day before the second anniversary 
of Diana's death in a 1997 Paris car crash. 

</P>
<P>
	Padres, Rockies To Open Season  
</P>
<P>
	MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) -- The National League champion San Diego  
Padres, stripped of stars Kevin Brown, Greg Vaughn and Ken 
Caminiti, begin defense of their crown tonight against the Colorado 
Rockies in the opener of the 1999 baseball season. It's the first 
time the national pastime will start a season outside of the United 
States and Canada. Colorado's Darryl Kile faces Andy Ashby in 
baseball's only game of the day. The other teams start play 
tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	Clemens To Take Mound As Yankee  
</P>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Roger Clemens will make his debut in  
Yankees threads tomorrow night when the team opens its season at 
Oakland. The five-time Cy Young Award winner was traded from the 
Toronto Blue Jays to the Yankees in mid-February for pitchers David 
Wells and Graeme Lloyd and second baseman Homer Bush. Because he'll 
be wearing the team's road grays, he won't start in the famed 
pinstripes until Saturday against Detroit. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  

</P>
