<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Santiago Wins Cuba's Baseball Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- A week later, it was no contest at Estadio  
Latinoamericano. 
</P>
<P>
	Back at the same ballpark where the Baltimore Orioles barely  
beat a Cuban all-star team, the deciding Game 7 of the Cuban 
national baseball series Sunday was a rout: Santiago 9, Havana 
Industriales 0. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the third time that Santiago won the championship, and  
first since 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Santiago forced a Game 7 with a win Saturday, then surprised  
tens of thousands of fans who turned out to cheer the hometown 
Industriales. 
</P>
<P>
	Gabriel Pierre hit a home run in the second inning and the team  
from eastern Cuba never let up. Adrian Hernandez, who recently won 
five key games for Havana, started but appeared weak. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Sunday, the Orioles held off the Cubans 3-2 in 11 innings.  
That Cuban team did not include any of the Havana or Santiago 
players -- they may play May 3 when an all-star team plays the 
Orioles at Baltimore's Camden Yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Santiago was tough all weekend despite missing four of its  
players. Fausto Alvarez, Jorge Tissert and Rey Isaac had to sit out 
because of injuries, and Pedro Poll was expelled during the final 
series. 
</P>
<P>
	Havana won the first two games of the series, putting itself in  
position for a ninth title. A week ago Saturday, the Industriales 
rallied for three runs in the bottom of the ninth, with a disputed 
call prompting more than a dozen Santiago players to surround the 
umpires -- one player even threw his glove into the face of an 
umpire. 
</P>
<P>
	Isla de la Juventud, from the island's southwestern coast, came  
in third in the series. Guantanamo, from Cuba's easternmost 
province, was fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	Humberto Rodriguez, president of the Sports Institute of Cuba,  
told the national news service Prensa Latina that the series had 
been ``a great victory for revolutionary baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This year's competition was so good, he said, that it had  
revived interest in the game and helped fill the stadiums again 
after a few years of dwindling attendance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
