<HEADLINE> Dodgers Make Moves, Keep Brumfield </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Dodgers got down to the  
25-man opening-day roster limit by making eight moves, including 
optioning outfielder Trenidad Hubbard to Triple-A Albuquerque of 
the Pacific Coast League. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't see this coming,'' said Hubbard, who hit .298 in 94  
games with the Dodgers last season. ``It's their team, whatever 
they want. I respect their decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Dodgers also optioned left-hander Jeff Kubenka to  
Albuquerque; designated left-hander Greg Cadaret and right-hander 
Arnold Gooch for assignment; placed right-hander Steve Montgomery 
on the 60-day disabled list, and purchased the contracts of 
outfielder Jacob Brumfield, catcher Rick Wilkins and left-handed 
pitcher Pedro Borbon, all of whom had signed minor league contracts 
previously. 
</P>
<P>
	The moves mean the Dodgers will have three catchers on their  
roster as the season begins -- starter Todd Hundley along with 
Wilkins and Paul LoDuca. 
</P>
<P>
	Hampered by soreness in his right elbow, where he had  
reconstructive surgery in 1997, Hundley played in only eight 
exhibition games. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think his legs are still not quite there yet,'' Dodgers  
manager Davey Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the three catchers, the Dodgers will start the  
season with 11 pitchers, seven infielders and only four 
outfielders. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest surprise of those making the team was 21-year-old  
left-handed reliever Onan Masaoka, who has never played in 
Triple-A, much less the majors. 
</P>
<P>
	Masaoka pitched in nine games this spring and allowed just one  
earned run in 13 innings. 
</P>
