<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Photographer Heads Into Full Career </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORTHFIELD, N.J. (AP) -- Alan Dumoff has heard the nicknames.  
Master of Disaster. Dr. Death. Ambulance Chaser. 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, he was there when a freak accident propelled a motorcyclist  
10 feet into a roadside tree. He photographed the victim. 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, he snapped away after a Dodge Neon collided with a truck,  
the doomed driver screaming, ``Someone help me!'' 
</P>
<P>
	And yes, he showed up when a car plowed into an insurance  
company office, his Nikon purring as paramedics strapped victims to 
stretchers. 
</P>
<P>
	Why not? You never know who might be willing to pay for the  
pictures. 
</P>
<P>
	Monitoring frequencies for police, fire and emergency medical  
service, the veteran freelance photographer hears dispatches and 
rushes in, sometimes beating the ambulances and fire trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	He sells photographs to newspapers, TV stations, personal injury  
lawyers, insurance adjusters, accident investigators. The more 
serious the accident, the more valuable the photos. 
</P>
<P>
	But he doesn't root for death or mayhem.  
</P>
<P>
	``Is it a pretty scene to see a 5-year-old get mangled in a car  
wreck? To see someone get burned alive in their car? No. But 
there's a reason things have to be documented,'' he says. ``Not 
every job has a pretty side.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dumoff cruises U.S. 40 near Atlantic City, awaiting his next  
call. His office is a red 1990 Toyota Land Cruiser, 307,489 miles 
on the odometer, four scanners on the dashboard. He doesn't seem to 
be listening until this crackle: ``... pedestrian MVA, 500 block of 
St. Louis Avenue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He knows the dispatchers' voices, can tell from the way they  
talk when the accident is unusual or, as perhaps in this ``motor 
vehicle accident,'' unusually severe. ``You start to get a feel for 
when something's out of the ordinary,'' he says, pulling a U-turn. 
</P>
<P>
	Another scanner crackles to life: A car has hit a building on  
U.S. 9. Another U-turn. 
</P>
<P>
	Dumoff learned news photography in his native Philadelphia from  
a former photo editor at the Philadelphia Daily News. 
</P>
<P>
	Too young to drive, he would shoot whatever he could find in the  
neighborhood. At age 18, he was hired by United Press International 
and headed to Vietnam where he quickly learned that a strong 
stomach was as crucial as a good camera. 
</P>
<P>
	``Here were people losing their lives, but it was my job to  
document it,'' he says. ``If it doesn't affect you, you're not 
alive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Back in the states, he earned bachelor's and master's degrees in  
photography. Then he turned into an accident addict, producing 
photographs -- sometimes too graphic for mass media -- that would 
help win a personal injury case or prosecute a drunken driver. 
</P>
<P>
	To foster business, he offers his copyrighted photographs free  
to police investigators. Everyone else pays -- a minimum of four 
8-by-10 color prints, $35 each. An acquaintance says Dumoff earns 
more than $100,000 a year. Dumoff demurs, saying only he ``does 
well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	How? ``Getting there as early as possible is a primary thing,''  
he says. ``The first 10 to 15 minutes are the key. That's when all 
the action is taking place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dumoff hops out at the scene where the luxury sedan plowed into  
a one-story office building, coming to rest amid crumbling plaster 
and shards of glass. 
</P>
<P>
	In 15 minutes, Dumoff shoots nearly a roll of film. Then he  
hangs around, chatting up rescue workers, pursuing the name of the 
building's owner. Surely he'll want photographs. Then there's the 
driver, the office manager, the two people inside who suffered 
minor injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	He gets names from police, squirreling them away for later, when  
he'll send a note on Dumoff Visual Evidence letterhead. ``Dear Sir: 
I photographed the scene of your accident. Sincerely, Alan 
Dumoff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then he waits for the phone to ring. It always does.  
</P>
<P>
	Often, the voice on the other end is that of a lawyer. Lawyers  
call Dumoff ``The Golden Key'' because his photographs can be 
pivotal in a civil suit. And while a picture may be worth a 
thousand words, Dumoff's can be worth far more.	   ``He can freeze in time conditions at the scene that you can 
never duplicate,'' says personal injury attorney Paul D'Amato of 
Atlantic City. He has used Dumoff photographs for 20 years. 
</P>
<P>
	At home, Dumoff monitors 22 scanners around the clock, and he's  
always ready to go. Clothes are laid out, ready to wear. His shoes 
have Velcro tabs. Laces would take too long to tie. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no such thing as time, weather, space or anything that  
deters ... . I can be out the door from a dead sleep in four 
minutes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The noise of his scanners drives his wife nuts. ``I turn them  
off,'' says Joan Bell, ``and he turns them on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dumoff does take time off, occasionally. The couple prefers  
cruise vacations for a complete getaway. Even then he carries a 
camera, for tropical sunsets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
