<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> At Least Six Killed in La. Twister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BENTON, La. (AP) -- Authorities searched through wreckage for  
additional victims on Easter morning after a tornado flattened 
homes and killed at least six people. 
</P>
<P>
	The twister swept through mobile home parks Saturday afternoon  
in the community just north of Shreveport. It was 300 yards wide 
when it passed through north Shreveport on its way to Benton, the 
National Weather Service said. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 30 homes were destroyed in the Twin Point Trailer Park,  
state police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bossier Parish County Sheriff Larry Deen confirmed Sunday  
morning that six people were killed -- a 14-year-old girl and five 
adults. State police earlier had reported nine deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	Deen said 100 people were treated at hospitals and released.  
</P>
<P>
	Deputy coroner Lisa Hayes said rescuers were still digging  
through debris and the death count could rise. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a major disaster ... so after we finish, who knows?''  
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Hay Meadow Trailer Park, twisted trees and overturned  
cars were mixed with the wreckage of homes. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't even tell it was a trailer park,'' said Johnny  
Johnson, manager of the Silver Dollar Bingo, a concrete block 
building next to the trailer park. ``It looks like a trash heap.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About the same time, a separate tornado destroyed the First  
United Methodist Church in Logansport, a DeSoto Parish town 
southwest of Shreveport near the Texas border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
