<HEADLINE> Baseball Or Beisbol, Game Is Same </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) -- The headline on the front page of  
Monterrey's biggest newspaper said it all -- ``Playball!'' 
</P>
<P>
	They may be saying it in Japan on opening day 2000, or maybe in  
Venezuela or Puerto Rico in the not-too-distant future. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball is beisbol, no matter the language or where it's  
played. Major league officials hope they've started a trend with 
Sunday night's historic international opener between the Colorado 
Rockies and San Diego Padres. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it just sets out the opening game,'' said Paul  
Beeston, baseball's No. 2 official. ``The opening game of baseball 
means something, and to take it international, I think it makes a 
statement for us that we believe in taking the game on a new 
direction. This is fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the landmark Saddle Mountain of the majestic eastern Sierra  
Madre towering in the distance beyond center field at Estadio 
Monterrey, baseball returned to Mexico, if just for one game. 
</P>
<P>
	The first opener outside of the United States and Canada, it was  
to be televised in more than 200 countries. And it was the only big 
league game in North America. 
</P>
<P>
	These two teams were natural. It was a homecoming for Rockies  
third baseman Vinny Castilla, a hero in his native Mexico. And the 
Padres, who started the trend of international ball by playing the 
first-ever series in Mexico in August 1996, want to be known as 
more than just Tijuana's team. 
</P>
<P>
	The Padres also moved a regular-season series to Hawaii in 1997.  
The Orioles played a historic exhibition game in Cuba a week ago, 
and many officials say other clubs should follow that lead. And the 
Mets and Expos played two well-received games in the Dominican 
Republic. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan might be next.  
</P>
<P>
	Playing a season-opening series in Japan has been in the  
discussion stage for the last year and a half. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope to bring it to closure in the next month or two, and  
if we can do that, we can open it over there,'' Beeston said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Seattle Mariners, whose majority owner is the Nintendo Corp.  
of Kobe, Japan, have expressed interest in playing in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	While the trailblazing Padres will likely continue to seek out  
exotic locales, it's clear they don't hold a monopoly on the idea. 
</P>
<P>
	``We like to think of ourselves as being in the vanguard, but  
frankly, the vanguard is expanding,'' Padres president Larry 
Lucchino said Sunday. ``There are lots of people in baseball who 
have awakened to the desirability and the inevitability of 
international baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said Rockies general manager Bob Gebhard: ``This is a sport that  
needs to expand and involve the entire world, not just the U.S. and 
Canada.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While going to Japan is the next logical step for baseball in  
general, the Padres have a strong bias toward Latin America, 
``given our desire to be Mexico's team,'' Lucchino said. 
</P>
<P>
	That desire was destined to take a back seat Sunday night  
because of Castilla's immense popularity. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, Lucchino said reaching out to all of Mexico helps  
the Padres with their identity in Baja California. He said future 
games could be played in Hermosillo, Culiacan or Guadalajara. 
</P>
<P>
	The Padres also would love to play games in Venezuela, homeland  
of catcher Carlos Hernandez, and Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	Beeston said Puerto Rico and Venezuela could currently handle  
big league games. Japan plays host to an annual postseason tour of 
big league all-stars. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball doesn't have a goal of having an international opener  
every year, Beeston said, ``but we'll certainly have to look at 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This game was a sellout and an adjoining Baseball Festival drew  
thousands of fans, particularly kids. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's healthy, it's exciting and it's fun,'' Beeston said.  
</P>
<P>
	Padres batting star Tony Gwynn said there were some reservations  
among the players about moving opening day. 
</P>
<P>
	``But once we got on the plane, everybody's looking forward to  
it. This is the first day of the season and there's always that 
excitement about the first game of the season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Leyland, making his debut as Rockies manager, agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is obviously a major day in the history of our game,'' he  
said. ``I think this is really a sign of things to come.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Padres will play their real home opener Tuesday afternoon,  
also against Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	There are obstacles in international games, like travel and  
cultural differences. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel lost,'' said Gwynn, who doesn't speak Spanish.  
</P>
<P>
	But, he added, ``once the hoopla's over, it's baseball. The  
baseball part of it will always be the same.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
