<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Glavine, Schilling Meet in Opener </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Forgotten in the hoopla over the Kevin  
Brown-Randy Johnson matchup is the pitching battle in Monday's 
opener between the Atlanta Braves and Philadelphia Phillies. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Glavine vs. Curt Schilling isn't exactly shabby.  
</P>
<P>
	Facing Schilling was Glavine's reward after winning the NL Cy  
Young Award last season. Greg Maddux started five of the previous 
six openers for the Braves. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's part of the territory,'' Glavine said. ``You're going to  
face other teams' No. 1 guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling, the subject of trade rumors all winter, was 15-14  
with a 3.25 ERA last season. He led the league with 300 strikeouts 
and 15 complete games as the third-place Phillies went 75-87, 31 
games behind the Braves in the NL East. 
</P>
<P>
	Glavine was 20-6 with a 2.47 ERA as the Braves won their seventh  
straight division title. His only previous opening day assignments 
were in 1990 and '92. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not pitching against Curt Schilling so much as I am  
pitching against his offense,'' Glavine said. ``I have to get those 
guys out and give our guys a chance to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Glavine allowed just one run in his last 15 innings during  
spring training. Schilling made his last spring training start on 
Wednesday, striking out seven in six innings against Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling likes his offense, which includes second-year third  
baseman Scott Rolen, who hit 31 home runs and drove in 110 a year 
ago; Rico Brogna, who hit 20 home runs and drove in 104 runs; and 
newly acquired Ron Gant, who had 26 home runs and 67 RBIs with the 
St. Louis Cardinals. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to score more runs. I don't think there's any  
question about that,'' Schilling said. 
</P>
<P>
	He threw 108 pitches against the Reds, and Philadelphia manager  
Terry Francona said Schilling is ready to throw about 120 pitches 
in the opener. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's very, very strong,'' Francona said.  
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta enters the season with two key losses: first baseman  
Andres Galarraga will miss the season because of a malignant tumor 
in his back, and closer Kerry Ligtenberg needs season-ending elbow 
surgery this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Galarraga hit 44 home runs and drove in 121 runs. Ligtenberg had  
30 saves in 34 chances as a rookie after Mark Wohlers had control 
problems that jeopardized his career. 
</P>
<P>
	The Braves, however, do have depth. During the offseason,  
Atlanta acquired second baseman Bret Boone from Cincinnati and 
signed free agent outfielders Brian Jordan and Otis Nixon. 
</P>
<P>
	Boone hit .266 with career highs in homers (24) and RBIs (95)  
last season. Nixon, who played with the Braves from 1991-93, 
returns after a year in which he hit a career-high .297 with 37 
steals in 110 games for the Minnesota Twins. Jordan hit .316 with 
25 homers and 91 RBIs last season with St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	Wohlers had a decent spring and is expected to reclaim his  
closer's job. If not, John Rocker, who pitched 12 shutout innings 
during the spring, could step in. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like our team. I think we're fine,'' Braves manager Bobby  
Cox said. ``Wohlers -- that has to be the one major thing that has 
happened this spring.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
